{
  "doc_id": "41239",
  "text": "Post-transcriptional gene silencing has become the fastest and most frequently used approach to reduce gene function in cell culture. In an organism without an interferon response, such as Drosophila melanogaster, RNA interference (RNAi) can be evoked using long, double-stranded RNAs [CITATION_1] . In order to achieve a gene knockdown at a stage not amenable to dsRNA injection into early embryos, transgenic approaches have been used in Drosophila [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Commonly, a 500 to 700 bp cDNA product is cloned as an inverted repeat with or without a spacer and expressed under the control of UASGal4 sequences [CITATION_4] . To allow tissuespecific and/or temporally controlled expression of the RNAi transgene, the bimodular UAS-Gal4 system can be used, bypassing any potential toxicity of such transgenes.",
  "correct_citation": {
